        ".     Severn had left England against his fathers wishes and with little money. In fact, his father was so incensed by his departure that, as Severn reported in a late memoir, in his insane rage he struck me a blow which fell me to the ground. Scott, Letters and Memoirs, p. 639 He was never to see his father again. While in Rome during the winter of 1820-21, Severn wrote numerous letters about Keats to their mutual friends in England, in particular William Haslam and ": null
